article.headline: Auburn 71, Arkansas 44
article.story:
FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Auburn coach Joe Ciampi used the
matchup zone defense that had worked in 599 previous victories to
get the 600th of his 27-year career.

Ciampi's No. 22 Lady Tigers shut down Arkansas' offense in
getting their 71-44 win Sunday.

"Defensively, I couldn't script a better execution of what we
had to do to beat a good Arkansas team," Ciampi said. "In terms
of communication and taking away the hot hand and rebounding, it
was a great team defense effort from everyone we had.

"You've got to play the game from inside-out, and that's been
our philosophy all along."

Ciampi is only the 10th Division I coach to reach the 600-win
plateau.

Auburn (15-4, 3-2 Southeastern Conference) held Arkansas to just
28.8 percent shooting, while forcing the Lady Backs into taking 32
3-pointers. Arkansas made only eight of those shots from long
distance.

Meanwhile, the Tigers were hitting 50 percent of their
field-goal attempts. Auburn also outrebounded Arkansas 46-27.

Auburn's LeCoe Willingham and Natasha Brackett combined for 38
points in the victory, the Lady Tigers' first in Fayetteville since
2000. Willingham also grabbed 10 rebounds.

Arkansas' leading scorer, Shameka Christon, who had been
averaging 22.7 points per game, was held by the Auburn zone to just
5 points on 2 of 9 shooting.

"To be honest, we really didn't have very many open looks,"
Christon said. "I couldn't really even get into a rhythm."

Auburn led just 32-29 at halftime. But the Lady Tigers stretched
that to 49-34 early in the second half on a 13-0 run using their
dominant inside game. Willingham scored 6 points during the run,
and Brackett added the last five.

The teams stayed close through much of the first half, until
Auburn's Marita Payne scored on a layup with 1:38 left to give the
Lady Tigers a 32-27 lead. The basket gave the 6-foot-5 Payne 8
points in just 11 minutes in the first half and highlighted
Auburn's dominance inside early.

The Lady Tigers outscored Arkansas 24-10 in the paint in the
first half, while Arkansas stayed close thanks to five first-half
3-pointers. Tigers outrebounded Arkansas 22-12 in the first half.

The Lady Razorbacks had a 13-12 lead early, after back-to-back
outside shots by Shanna Harmon. Two more straight 3-pointers by
Rochelle Vaughn later in the half pushed Arkansas to its largest
lead, 23-19.

Auburn reclaimed the lead at 25-23 on Payne' second inside
basket of the half, and the Lady Tigers went on a 13-4 run to go
ahead 32-27 before Arkansas' Kristin Moore scored inside to close
the half and bring the Lady Razorbacks within three points at
32-29.

Vaughn finished the game with 12 points, the only double-digit
scorer for Arkansas.

"They were giving us the outside shot," Arkansas coach Susie
Gardner said. "We had open looks, but we just missed."
